title: For Sale:  Beautifull .22 short Smooth Bore  Parlor Rifle
postcontent: I have the really nice example of an antique Flobert parlor or gallery gun in very nice, working condition. It has a nice walnut stock, 23" octagon barrel, brass bead front and buckhorn leaf rear sight. The gun functions as it should, and is fun to shoot! I would recommend that you only shoot low-pressure "CB" shorts in it, as even these rounds probably exceed the original black powder proofs for that rifle. That being said, the barrel is quite thick with no flaws that I can see. What makes this rifle unique is the firing design. Basically the rear of the "bolt" that closes over the round has the firing pin cast in it, and it fires the round when it closes (when the trigger is pulled). It's very interesting.   At short distances (indoor shooting ranges, etc) it is very accurate.  .22 Shotshells can also be fired from it with a nice pattern (like a shotgun, NOT like a rifle, where all the shot is thrown to the outside of the pattern).It's been a great little keepsake, but now it's time to move it to someone else who can cherish it. I live near Mt Vernon, Burlington, Sedro-Woolley, and can meet you near I-5. This gun was made prior to 1898, so it can be sold direct without any transfer. I will need to see ID though. Sorry, but I'm not really interested in any trades (never hurts to ask though!), and the price is firm.Thanks for looking, and have a great day!

postcontent: For sale is an M1 Garand double-sized training rifle. This large training aid was originally used by the military to teach the inner workings of the normal sized M1 Garand to new recruits. This is not a firing model and cannot be converted to fire ammunition. It measures 7ft. 2.5 in long and has a "US" Navy marking on the left side of the receiver. The operating rod, spring, bolt, and follower assembly all function just like the real version of the rifle when the action is cycled. The gas cylinder lock on the end of the barrel is removeable. The rifle is missing the trigger assembly, which is common with a military item of this age. These cutaway rifles are rare and don't come up for sale very often. This would make a great addition to anyone's military collection, man cave, or gun shop. It always draws a crowd and complete versions of these training rifles typically sell for around $1,500.00.
